WILLAMETTE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING, LLC USES A SERVICE MARK OF THREE TREES ON A HILL WITH THE WORDS" WILLAMETTE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING, LLC A CLEANER AIR AND WATER COMPANY."  THE SERVICE MARK TEXT SAYS:  "WILLAMETTE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING, LLC"  WITH THE TEXT "A CLEANER AIR AND WATER COMPANY" BELOW IT.  THE LETTER "W" IN "WILLAMETTE" HAS TWO GAPS IN IT:  ONE GAP SEPARATES EACH OF THE INWARD LINES OF THE W.  THE LETTER "E" IN "ENVIRONMENTAL" AND THE LETTER "E" IN ENGINEERING" ARE THREE EQUILATERALLY SPACED BARS OF EQUAL LENGTH WITH NO VERTICAL LINE CONNECTING THE BARS TOGETHER.  THE FONT OF THE WORDS "WILLAMETTE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING, LLC" IS A BOLD SANS SERIF FONT.  THE SERIF FONT OF THE CORDS "A CLEANER AIR AND WATER COMPANY" IS NOT BOLDED.  THE THE LEFT OF THE ABOVE TEXT IS A DRAWN PICTURE OF THREE TREES ON A HILL WITH TWO CLOUDS ABOVE THEM.  THE HILL IS A SINGLE SLIGHTLY CURVING LINE WHICH HAS AN APEX AT ABOUT THE CENTER OF THE HILL AND SLOPES DOWN TO EITHER SIDE.  THE TREE ON THE FAR LEFT IS DEPICTED TO BE ON THE FRONT OF THE HILL AND IS LARGER THAN THE OTHER TWO TREES, WHICH ARE BOTH OF THE SAME SIZE AND TYPE.  THE LARGER TREE HAS ONE VERTICAL LINE WHICH PASSES THROUGH THE CURED HILL LINE. THAT VERTICAL TREE LINE HAS FOUR UPWARD ARROWS DISSECTING IT.  EACH ARROW CONNECTS WITH THE CENTRAL VERTICAL LINE AT A 45-DEGREE ANGLE.  THE TWO TREES TO THE RIGHT OF THE ABOVE-DESCRIBED LARGER TREE ARE DEPICTED TO BE ON THE HILL.  ONE VERTICAL LINE FOR EACH TREE CONNECTS, BUT DOES NOT PASS THROUGH, THE CURVE REPRESENTING THE HILL.  EACH VERTICAL TREE LINE HAS THREE UPWARD ARROWS CONNECTING TO THE VERTICAL LINE AT A 45-DEGREE ANGLE.  ABOVE THE TREES, BEGINNING ABOVE THE MIDDLE TREE, ARE TWO IDENTICAL CLOUDS, WITH ONE PARTIALLY STACKED ON TOP OF THE OTHER.  EACH OF CLOUDS HAVE A BULBOUS SHAPE; EACH CLOUD IS A SINGLE, CONTINUOUS LINE.  THE FAR-LEFT PORTION OF THE LINE FORMS A QUARTER CIRCLE, WHICH IS CONNECTED TO A HALF-CIRCLE, WHICH IS THE HIGHEST POINT IN THE CLOUD. THE LINE THEN MAKES A SMALLER QUARTER CIRCLE AND TURNS INTO A SHORT HORIZONTAL LINE.
